r I in France. Told from the perspective of ordinary women and men caught in the flood of mobilization, this revealing book deepens our understanding of the traumatic impact of war on soldiers and civilians alike.  August 1914 was a finalist for a prestigious French book award, the Prix Fémina for nonfiction, in 2014.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zFrance. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh1 aO'Hara, Stephanie08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066771440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300224948423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300224948.jpg  a978-3-11-066771-4  YUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO